u003eFaulty Thermostat:\u003c/strong\u003e Sometimes, the thermostat may need recalibration or replacement to ensure the system is running at the correct temperature.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWater Supply Problems:\u003c/strong\u003e A blocked water line or malfunctioning valve could be preventing water from reaching your machine. This is often an easy fix that doesn’t require a replacement.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhat to Do:\u003c/strong\u003e If the issue seems relatively simple, a technician can likely resolve it through repairs, helping you save on the high upfront cost of replacing your entire unit.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003ch3\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e2. The Machine is Still Relatively New\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/h3\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eIf your ice machine is less than 5-7 years old and has only experienced minor problems, it may be worth repairing. Commercial ice machines are built to last, and repairs can often extend the life of the machine for several more years.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003ch4\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhat to Look For:\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/h4\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eAge of the Unit:\u003c/strong\u003e Newer machines generally have more advanced technology, making them easier and cheaper to repair.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWarranty Coverage:\u003c/strong\u003e If your unit is still under warranty, repairs might be more cost-effective and covered by the manufacturer.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhat to Do:\u003c/strong\u003e Check if your ice machine is still under warranty or if you have a maintenance plan that could reduce repair costs. This can make repairs a much more affordable option.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003ch2\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhen to Replace Your Ice Machine\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/h2\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eWhile repairs are often a viable option, there are situations where replacing your ice 